      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To present the debate neutrally, you are entirely correct to acknowledge the textualist viewpoint, which insists the Constitution's meaning is fixed and should not be subject to judicial reinterpretation. This school of thought argues that judges should strictly adhere to the original intent of the framers to prevent the judiciary from becoming a legislative body. However, the proponents of substantive due process argue that a static reading ignores the fundamental, evolving needs of a free society.",
      "source": "target",
